            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Canada Taxes Calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool gives you a simplified estimate of your Canadian
                income tax burden. It combines
                <strong>federal tax</strong>,
                <strong>provincial or territorial tax</strong>, and optional
                <strong>CPP</strong> and <strong>EI</strong> contributions to
                show your approximate <strong>take‑home pay</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Taxable income</h3>
              <p>Your taxable income is calculated as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  Taxable income = Employment income + Other taxable income −
                  RRSP contributions − Other deductions
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>
                In reality, taxable income can also be affected by things like
                capital gains, dividends, business income, and specific
                deductions. Here we focus on a clean, employment‑income‑based
                estimate for clarity.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Federal tax brackets (progressive)</h3>
              <p>
                Canada uses a <strong>progressive</strong> tax system: each
                slice of your income is taxed at a different rate. For example,
                for a recent year the federal brackets (rounded) look like:
              </p>
              <div class="table-scroll">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left">Taxable income band</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left">Federal rate</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">Up to about $55,000</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">15%</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">Next portion to ~ $110,000</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">20.5%</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">Next portion to ~ $165,000</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">26%</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">Next portion to ~ $235,000</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">29%</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">Above that</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-1">33%</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator applies each rate only to the income that falls
                within that band, then sums the results to get your total
                federal tax before credits.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Provincial and territorial tax</h3>
              <p>
                Each province and territory has its own progressive tax
                brackets. To keep the tool fast and easy to use, we approximate
                these with a small set of brackets and rates for each region.
                The logic is the same as for federal tax: each slice of income
                is taxed at its own rate.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Non‑refundable tax credits (simplified)</h3>
              <p>
                Canada’s system includes many
                <strong>non‑refundable tax credits</strong>, such as the basic
                personal amount, spousal amount, age amount, disability amount,
                and more.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator models credits in a simplified way: it assumes a
                basic personal amount and small additional credits for a spouse
                and children, then multiplies the total credit base by the
                lowest federal and provincial rates to reduce your tax payable.
              </p>

              <h3>5. CPP and EI contributions</h3>
              <p>
                If you choose to include CPP and EI, the calculator estimates:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>CPP contributions</strong> on employment income
                  between a lower and upper limit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>EI premiums</strong> on insurable earnings up to an
                  annual maximum.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Both CPP and EI have annual maximums; once your income exceeds
                those, contributions stop increasing. The calculator caps
                contributions at those approximate maximums.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Average vs marginal tax rate</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average tax rate</strong> = (Federal tax + Provincial
                  tax) ÷ Gross income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal tax rate</strong> = the combined rate on your
                  <em>next</em> dollar of income, based on the bracket you are
                  currently in.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Your marginal rate is always higher than your average rate in a
                progressive system. The calculator shows both so you can
                understand how an extra dollar of income or RRSP contribution
                affects you.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This is an educational tool, not an official CRA calculator.
                </li>
                <li>Rates and thresholds are simplified and rounded.</li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> handle all special cases (capital
                  gains inclusion rate, eligible vs non‑eligible dividends,
                  complex credits, benefits, or provincial surcharges).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Quebec has its own pension and parental insurance systems;
                  here we approximate CPP/EI style contributions for comparison
                  only.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For official guidance, always refer to the
                <a
                  href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency.html"
                  rel="nofollow noopener"
                  target="_blank"
                  >Canada Revenue Agency (CRA)</a
                >
                or a qualified tax professional.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ: Canada taxes</h2>

              <h3>Do I pay tax on worldwide income in Canada?</h3>
              <p>
                If you are a
                <strong>resident of Canada for tax purposes</strong>, you
                generally pay tax on your worldwide income, with foreign tax
                credits available to avoid double taxation. If you are a
                non‑resident, you are usually taxed only on certain
                Canadian‑source income.
              </p>

              <h3>How do RRSP contributions reduce my tax?</h3>
              <p>
                RRSP contributions reduce your <strong>taxable income</strong>.
                The tax savings are roughly your
                <strong>marginal tax rate × RRSP contribution</strong>. For
                example, if your marginal combined rate is 35% and you
                contribute $5,000, your tax bill may drop by about $1,750.
              </p>

              <h3>Which province has the lowest income tax?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on your income level. At many income levels, Alberta
                and some territories have lower combined rates, while Quebec and
                some Atlantic provinces can be higher. Use the comparison
                feature to see how your net income changes by province.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator suitable for self‑employed people?</h3>
              <p>
                It can give a rough idea if you treat your net business income
                as “employment income”, but it does not model all
                self‑employment deductions, CPP self‑employed contributions, or
                GST/HST obligations. Self‑employed taxpayers should use this as
                a high‑level guide only.
